{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Pseudo-elements","slug":"css-pseudo-elements","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Pseudo-classes"],"learning_objectives":["Understand difference between :: and :","Use ::before","Use ::after","Use ::first-letter","Use ::first-line"],"theory":"A CSS pseudo-element is used to style specified parts of an element.\n\n*   `::before`: Inserts content BEFORE the content of the selected element.\n*   `::after`: Inserts content AFTER the content of the selected element.\n*   `::first-letter`: Styles the first letter of the text.\n*   `::first-line`: Styles the first line of the text.\n\nDouble colon `::` is the modern syntax for pseudo-elements (vs single `:` for pseudo-classes).","syntax":"p::before {\n  content: \"Read this: \";\n  font-weight: bold;\n}","examples":[{"code":"/* Add quotes automatically */\nq::before {\n  content: open-quote;\n}\nq::after {\n  content: close-quote;\n}","output":"Adds quotation marks around <q> tags.","explanation":"Semantic way to handle quotes."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Forgetting the 'content' property","correction":"::before and ::after DO NOT Work without the `content` property, even if it's an empty string.","example":"content: '';"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is the difference between specificities of pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements?","answer":"They basically have the same specificity (0,0,1,0), similar to a class.","difficulty":"Hard"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Make the first letter of a paragraph 50px large (Drop Cap).","hint":"Use ::first-letter.","solution":"p::first-letter { font-size: 50px; }","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Custom Custom Checkboxes","description":"Developers hide the default checkbox and use `::before` on a label to draw a custom box.","code":"input[type=\"checkbox\"] + label::before { content: ''; ... }"}],"exam_notes":["You ca